INSTITUTE FOR ADVANCED METASCIENTIFIC ACCOUNTABILITY (IAMA)
White Paper Series No. 47-B
On the Administrative Simulation of Scientific Authority in the Absence of Demonstrable Scientific Output

⸻

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This white paper addresses the growing institutional phenomenon of Performative Scientific Authority Without Corresponding Experimental Burden (PSAWCEB), a condition in which individuals adopt the rhetorical posture, aesthetic presentation, and public authority of practicing scientists while producing negligible primary scientific output. The Institute has identified this phenomenon as a Category II Epistemic Risk due to its capacity to (a) redefine science as commentary about science, (b) replace empirical labor with discursive positioning, and (c) create a self-reinforcing prestige loop in which authority is derived primarily from explaining why others are wrong rather than demonstrating what is correct.

The subject of this report has been selected as a representative case study in Recursive Science Commentary Substitution (RSCS), wherein commentary on scientific misunderstandings becomes operationally indistinguishable from scientific activity itself, despite the absence of new experimental data, falsifiable predictions, or measurable research programs.

The urgency of this report is administrative rather than scientific.

