1. DEFINITIONS AND TERMINOLOGY

1.1 Scientific Activity (SA)

For the purposes of this report, Scientific Activity is defined as any process that produces at least one of the following:
	•	A testable hypothesis
	•	A reproducible experiment
	•	A novel mathematical model with predictive power
	•	Measurable data not previously recorded
	•	A method enabling any of the above

1.2 Science Commentary (SC)

Science Commentary is defined as:

The explanation, interpretation, criticism, or popularization of existing scientific work without producing new empirical or theoretical results.

1.3 Commentary Inflation Event (CIE)

A Commentary Inflation Event occurs when Science Commentary is presented, institutionally or rhetorically, as equivalent to Scientific Activity.

⸻

2. METHODOLOGY

The Institute employed the Quantitative Output-to-Commentary Ratio (QOCR) model:

QOCR = \frac{E + H + P + D}{C}

Where:
	•	E = Number of experiments conducted
	•	H = Number of testable hypotheses proposed
	•	P = Number of peer-reviewed primary research papers
	•	D = Number of original datasets produced
	•	C = Number of hours of commentary about science

When QOCR \rightarrow 0, the subject transitions from Scientist to Science Commentator With Authority Aesthetic (SCWAA).

Due to the absence of measurable E, H, and D, the Institute was forced to divide by a very large C, producing a QOCR value that approached administrative zero.

This required the creation of a new unit: The Millihypothesis (mH), defined as a hypothesis that is implied rhetorically but never operationalized experimentally.

The subject produced an estimated 3,400 mH/year, none of which were observed to evolve into full Hypothesis Units (HU).

