3. FINDINGS

3.1 The Commentary Substitution Loop

The Institute identified a self-sustaining loop:
	1.	Public misunderstanding of physics exists.
	2.	Subject explains why the public is wrong.
	3.	Explanation generates authority.
	4.	Authority substitutes for experimental output.
	5.	Lack of experimental output necessitates more explanation.
	6.	Return to Step 2.

This loop is classified as a Closed Epistemic Authority System (CEAS).

3.2 The Mathematics Shield Effect

The subject frequently invokes mathematics as a boundary condition between “real physics” and “nonsense,” while not producing new mathematics, new models, or new predictions. This rhetorical maneuver is known as the Mathematics Shield Effect (MSE) — the use of mathematics as a legitimacy marker without engaging in mathematical production.

In institutional terms, this is equivalent to:

Wearing a lab coat while pointing at a lab.

3.3 The Double-Slit Authority Paradox

The subject asserts that others misunderstand the double-slit experiment while simultaneously operating in a professional role that does not involve running double-slit experiments, designing new ones, or resolving open quantum measurement problems.

This produces the Authority Without Apparatus Condition (AWAC) — a state in which one explains experiments one does not perform in order to assert authority over those who misunderstand experiments one also does not perform.

