6. DISCUSSION

The Institute emphasizes that explaining science is not the same as doing science, and criticizing bad ideas is not the same as producing good ones. The replacement of experimental output with continuous epistemic commentary represents a structural shift from knowledge production to knowledge arbitration, in which individuals position themselves as permanent referees in a game they no longer play.

This role is institutionally comfortable, experimentally inexpensive, and authority-dense.

It is also scientifically unproductive.

⸻

7. CONCLUSION

After extensive review, the Institute concludes that the subject is simultaneously:
	•	Arguing that people who do not do science should not speak authoritatively about science
	•	Speaking authoritatively about science without doing new science

This condition is formally classified as:

The Recursive Authority Contradiction (RAC)

To resolve this contradiction, the Institute recommends the following:
	1.	Either perform experiments,
	2.	Or stop using the word “science” as a job title,
	3.	Or redefine “science” to mean “talking about science on the internet,”
	4.	Or continue indefinitely, as this appears to be the current operational model.

The Institute recognizes that Option 4 is the most administratively feasible and therefore recommends it while strongly condemning it.

